<p>Indiana sits at the crossroads of American manufacturing and logistics, leveraging its central location and extensive highway and rail network to become one of the country's most logistics-intensive states. Indianapolis anchors the state economy as a mid-sized but highly productive metropolitan area -- Eli Lilly and Company (one of the world's largest pharmaceutical companies) is headquartered in Indianapolis, Salesforce has its Midwest headquarters there, and the city is home to the NASCAR IndyCar racing industry and related motorsports technology. The Cummins engine plant in Columbus, the Honda manufacturing facility in Lincoln City (one of Honda's most important US plants), and steel mills along the Indiana-Illinois border reflect the state's manufacturing depth. Northern Indiana (South Bend, Elkhart) is the RV capital of the world, producing over 80% of recreational vehicles sold in the United States.</p>

<p>Indiana has one of the simplest tax structures of any state with an income tax: a flat 3.05% state rate, among the lowest flat rates in the country. Additionally, Indiana counties levy their own income taxes ranging from 0.5% to 2.9%, which are withheld through employer payroll. This generator calculates Indiana's state tax and all federal taxes to produce a complete, accurate pay stub PDF.</p>

<h2>Indiana Income Tax Rates</h2>

<p>Indiana uses a flat state income tax rate of 3.05% (2024 rate). Indiana has been reducing its flat income tax rate in steps -- it was 3.23% prior to 2024, and further reductions are scheduled through upcoming tax years. Indiana's trajectory mirrors several other Midwestern states in gradually reducing income taxes in response to competitive pressures.</p>

<p>Indiana provides a personal exemption ($1,000 per exemption in 2024) and a renter's deduction for qualifying renters ($3,000 maximum deduction from rent paid), along with other specific deductions. The standard calculation for pay stub purposes applies the 3.05% rate to gross wages with modest adjustments.</p>

<p><strong>Indiana county income taxes:</strong> Every county in Indiana levies a county income tax (COIT) on residents and, in some counties, non-residents working in that county. These rates vary significantly:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Marion County (Indianapolis): 2.02%</li>
  <li>Hamilton County (Carmel/Noblesville): 1.1%</li>
  <li>Allen County (Fort Wayne): 1.48%</li>
  <li>Tippecanoe County (Lafayette): 1.4%</li>
  <li>Elkhart County (Elkhart/Mishawaka): 1.5%</li>
  <li>Lake County (Gary/Hammond -- Indiana side of Chicago metro): 1.5%</li>
</ul>

<p>The total state plus county income tax rate for most Indiana workers is in the range of 4.05% to 5.95% of wages. For Marion County (Indianapolis) residents: 3.05% state + 2.02% county = 5.07% combined rate.</p>

<h2>Does Indiana Require Pay Stubs?</h2>

<p>Indiana does not have a state law requiring private employers to provide pay stubs to employees. The Indiana Wage Payment Statute focuses on timely payment and proper deductions but does not mandate written wage statements. Federal FLSA requirements apply, but Indiana does not add a state requirement on top.</p>

<p>Most Indiana employers provide pay stubs voluntarily, particularly the large manufacturers (Honda, Cummins, Eli Lilly) and logistics companies (Hertz, Amazon fulfillment centers). For the significant small manufacturing and construction workforce in Indiana that works for smaller employers with less sophisticated payroll systems, this generator provides needed income documentation. No Indiana law requires employers to provide pay stubs, but federal FLSA §211(c) requires employers to maintain payroll records for a minimum of three years.</p>

<h2>Pay Stub Requirements in Indiana</h2>

<p>A complete Indiana pay stub should include all standard elements:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Employer name and address</li>
  <li>Employee name and identifier</li>
  <li>Pay period dates</li>
  <li>Pay date</li>
  <li>Hours worked (hourly employees)</li>
  <li>Regular and overtime hours and rates</li>
  <li>Gross wages</li>
  <li>Indiana state income tax withheld (3.05%)</li>
  <li>Indiana county income tax withheld (county rate for the employee's county)</li>
  <li>Federal income tax withheld</li>
  <li>Social Security and Medicare withheld</li>
  <li>Any voluntary deductions</li>
  <li>Net pay</li>
  <li>Year-to-date totals</li>
</ul>

<p>The county income tax line is important -- failure to include it, or applying the wrong county rate, means the stub does not accurately reflect deductions. Workers moving between Indiana counties may have different county rates apply as of the date they change residency.</p>

<h2>Pay Frequency Laws in Indiana</h2>

<p>Indiana Code § 22-2-5-1 requires that employers pay wages at least semi-monthly (twice per month). Wages must be paid within ten days of the end of the regular pay period. Most Indiana manufacturers pay bi-weekly, which satisfies this requirement.</p>

<p>Indiana does not have specific pay frequency requirements for different worker categories -- the semi-monthly minimum applies to all workers. The manufacturing-heavy Indiana economy has standardized on bi-weekly pay cycles, which work well with plant production schedules.</p>

<h2>Indiana's Manufacturing and Industrial Workforce</h2>

<p><strong>Automotive and manufacturing workers:</strong> Indiana is one of the most manufacturing-intensive states in the country by GDP share. Honda's Lincoln/Greensburg plants, Subaru's Lafayette plant, Stellantis operations, Toyota's Princeton truck plant, and hundreds of automotive suppliers employ a huge manufacturing workforce. These are typically well-paying union or near-union wages with complex pay stubs that include base wages, overtime (automotive plants routinely run overtime during high-demand periods), and any union benefits deductions. For home purchases in communities like Columbus, Greensburg, or Lafayette, these workers need detailed income documentation.</p>

<p><strong>Pharmaceutical workers at Eli Lilly:</strong> Eli Lilly is Indiana's largest private employer, with its global headquarters and major manufacturing facilities in Indianapolis. Lilly manufactures insulin, Mounjaro (the diabetes/GLP-1 drug), and numerous other medications at its Indianapolis and Branchburg plants. Research scientists, manufacturing technicians, commercial employees, and administrative staff across a wide pay range need income documentation for Indianapolis's growing housing market. Lilly's stock performance and employee stock purchase programs add complexity to compensation documentation.</p>

<p><strong>RV industry workers in Elkhart:</strong> The Elkhart-Goshen metropolitan area produces over 80% of the recreational vehicles manufactured in the United States -- Winnebago, Forest River, Airstream, Coachmen, and dozens of smaller manufacturers are all based in or near Elkhart. These are primarily hourly manufacturing jobs, and the RV industry is sensitive to consumer confidence and interest rates. During boom periods, Elkhart workers earn substantial overtime. Documentation of overtime-heavy periods alongside slower periods helps workers demonstrate average income accurately.</p>

<p><strong>Logistics workers at Amazon and FedEx:</strong> Indiana's logistics sector is enormous given its central location. Amazon has multiple fulfillment centers (in Whitestown, Greenwood, Jeffersonville), FedEx Ground has major facilities, and UPS has significant Indiana operations. Warehouse workers, many of whom are hourly with variable hours, need income documentation for housing in Indianapolis suburbs and smaller Indiana cities.</p>


