<h2>Frequently Asked Questions for Indiana Workers</h2>

<h3>I live in Hamilton County but work in Marion County. Which county's tax rate applies?</h3>
<p>Indiana county income tax (COIT) is based on residency, not work location. If you live in Hamilton County (1.1% rate), you pay Hamilton County's tax rate on all your Indiana income regardless of where you work. Your employer withholds based on your home county, not the county where the workplace is located. This is different from some states where the city or county of employment imposes a tax on non-residents. Indiana's COIT is a resident tax. When generating pay stubs, use the county tax rate for the county where you live, not where you work.</p>

<h3>Indiana's flat rate is 3.05%. Is that one of the lowest in the country?</h3>
<p>Yes, Indiana's 3.05% flat rate is one of the lowest income tax rates of any state that levies an income tax. For comparison: Illinois is 4.95%, Ohio ranges from 2.765% to 3.99%, Michigan is 4.25%, and Pennsylvania is 3.07%. Of the Midwest's manufacturing states, Indiana and Pennsylvania have the two lowest flat rates. When combined with Marion County's 2.02% COIT, Indianapolis residents pay about 5.07% combined state plus local, which is comparable to Ohio's moderate earners but lower than Illinois. For workers comparing offers between Indiana and neighboring states, Indiana's lower income tax (partially offset by the county tax) is a meaningful take-home pay advantage.</p>

<h3>Does Indiana have any paid family leave or state disability insurance?</h3>
<p>No. Indiana has no state-mandated paid family leave or disability insurance funded through employee payroll deductions. Indiana workers who need income replacement during medical leave or family care situations must rely on employer-provided programs (PTO, employer-sponsored short-term disability insurance) or private insurance. Indiana's payroll deductions are limited to the state income tax (3.05%), the applicable county income tax (0.5%-2.9%), and federal taxes. This is consistent with Indiana's generally conservative, business-friendly regulatory approach that tends toward minimal mandatory employer and employee costs.</p>

<h3>I work on the assembly line at Honda in Lincoln. How does overtime affect my paycheck?</h3>
<p>Overtime at an assembly plant can significantly affect bi-weekly pay. Federal and Indiana law both require time-and-a-half (1.5x) for hours over 40 in a workweek. Indiana does not have daily overtime rules. At Honda Lincoln (which manufactures the CR-V and Civic), mandatory overtime during high-production periods can add $400-$800 or more to a bi-weekly paycheck. For income documentation purposes, generating stubs based on actual earned wages (including overtime) for each pay period gives the most accurate picture of your income. Provide multiple stubs covering different pay periods to show the range -- some periods with overtime, some without -- so lenders and landlords understand your income pattern. The <a href="/hourly-pay-stub-template">hourly pay stub template</a> shows how to document regular and overtime hours on the same stub.</p>

<h3>Indiana's RV industry has boom-and-bust cycles. How do I document variable income?</h3>
<p>RV industry wages can swing significantly based on consumer demand. During strong periods, workers earn substantial base pay plus overtime. During slowdowns, hours may be reduced. For income documentation, generate stubs reflecting the actual pay for each period, without inflating wages during good periods or creating averages that do not match actual pay. Lenders who see highly variable income typically want 12-24 months of documentation and calculate income on an averaged or annualized basis. For an RV worker with variable income seeking a mortgage, the <a href="/pay-stub-for-mortgage">pay stub for mortgage</a> guide covers how underwriters handle variable income documentation specifically.</p>

